# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-delaware] The **1789 United States House of Representatives election in Delaware** was held on January 7, 1789.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-delaware] The former Continental Congressman John Vining won the election and became Delaware's first Representative to the House of Representatives.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Congressional elections to the 1st United States Congress were held in Georgia on February 9, 1789, for the state's three congressional districts.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] All elected representatives were members of the Anti-Administration political faction in Congress.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Georgia Election Act of 1789 established a mixed at-large/district system for congressional elections.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Under the act, representatives were elected at-large on a general ticket but for three district-based seats, for which candidates were required to be residents.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Each voter was allowed to cast three votes, one for a candidate in each district.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Some candidates received votes in multiple districts.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The election returns were opened on February 26.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Only the returns of Richmond, Wilkes, Effingham, Chatham, Liberty, Burke, and Washington Counties were counted, as they had been received in time.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The returns from Greene, Glynn, and Camden Counties came in too late but were published anyways.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] All elected representatives would've won with the returns of those counties included.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Lower District was also known as the Eastern District or the First District.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Jackson led a Savannah-based political faction, referred to as the Jackson party, centered in Coastal Georgia.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Middle District was also known as the Center District or the Second District.
[src:1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Upper District was also known as the Western District or the Third District.
